top_reviews.title: Worth the Upgrade
top_reviews.review_text: The PS4 Pro offers some nice advantages over the base slim model. Graphics and resolution are noticeably better and frame rates show improvement. The difference is not a generational leap but it is certainly nice for a mid cycle upgrade. If you own a 4K tv and are buying your first console, definitely buy the Pro. For those looking to upgrade, it's more subjective. Especially for those with 1080p televisions and no HDR. The biggest complaint so far is the usage of the same CPU as the slim model, just slightly overclocked. Do not expect 30fps games to jump to 60fps.

top_reviews.title: Nice improvement to an already great system.
top_reviews.review_text: Great console with noticeable improvement in graphics with some games. If you already own a PS4 it would be hard to justify upgrading to this version of the system, but newcomers should definitely consider this hardware.

top_reviews.title: Love it!

top_reviews.title: Worth the money if you can find it.
top_reviews.review_text: After reading several reviews it seems necessary to write an actually review. If you own a ps4 the ps5 is quite in comparison.(don't believe the negative reviews.) I've ran the system for 72 hours straight it has no heating issues. Most of the games I've tested are beautiful graphically and run extremely smooth.(Demon Souls and Assassins Creed Valhalla are the games I've tested and I was not disappointed.) Most games load within 1/10 of the time of the ps4. You can link the ps4 and ps5 to play to some of the games. (Not all ps4 games play well on the system.) The control is a little big in comparison but if you played xbox it's about the same size, it is more responsive than the ps4 controller, it is heavier than ps4 and xbox. In all I'm extremely impressed with the ps5 so far normally I expect some issues with a newly launched system but so far everything has been extremely smooth.

Item.title: Nintendo Switch with Gray Joy-Con
Item.description:
Introducing Nintendo Switch, the new home video game system from Nintendo. In addition to providing single and multiplayer thrills at home, the Nintendo Switch system can be taken on the go so players can enjoy a full home console experience anytime, anywhere. The mobility of a handheld is now added to the power of a home gaming system, with unprecedented new play styles brought to life by the two new Joy-Con controllers.

PLAY ANYWHERE

At home the system rests in the Nintendo Switch dock, which lets you play with family and friends on a TV in the comfort of your living room.

By simply lifting Nintendo Switch from the dock at any time, the system instantly transitions to handheld mode, and the same great gaming experience that was being enjoyed at home now travels with you. The portability of Nintendo Switch is enhanced by its 6.2-inch screen, which displays bright, high-definition gameplay at the park, on an airplane, in a car, or at a friend's apartment.

Nintendo Switch comes with two Joy-Con that can each act as a standalone controller with an analog stick, a full complement of face and shoulder buttons, built in motion-sensing technology and new HD Rumble. They can be inserted into a Joy-Con grip accessory to be used like a traditional controller, held comfortably in each hand for independent left and right motion controls, or shared between two players for instant multiplayer gaming in front of the TV or out on the go.

This bundle includes the Nintendo Switch console and Nintendo Switch dock in black, and left and right Joy‑Con controllers in a contrasting gray. It also includes all the extras you need to get started.

top_reviews.review_text: I love Nintendo branded games. I mainly play most of my games on PS4 though. So, this will not replace it. The system is great overall. I love how quick it is. This is a mobile device. It'd be great for a combined gaming/media device. One thing this system does that Sony has yet to figure out with their Playstation Store is providing you with the chance to put games on your "Wishlist". Steam does this for PC games, and emails you when something on your wishlist goes on sale. I've yet to see an email from Nintendo for something like this, but I have high hopes they will do this as well. I still recommend the system, but only if you really want access to Nintendo's first party games or you expect to spend a lot of time playing away from home. You get much more functionality from a PC, PS4 or Xbox otherwise.
